      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Body Corporate Disputes and QCAT: What Sellers of Queensland Units Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        An active body corporate dispute is one of the most frequently missed disclosure items when selling a Queensland unit. Here is how disputes work, what sellers must disclose, and what a buyer's records search will find.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Body corporate disputes in Queensland range from minor disagreements between neighbours about noise or pets, to serious legal proceedings involving the whole scheme against a builder over defective construction. For sellers of units and townhouses, the critical question is not whether disputes are common, they are, but whether the disputes involving your building or your lot are active, material, and required to be disclosed before you accept an offer. Getting this wrong is one of the more expensive mistakes a strata seller can make, because a buyer who discovers an undisclosed dispute mid-campaign has several options, none of which are comfortable for the vendor.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common types of body corporate disputes in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Disputes in community titles schemes arise most often between lot owners, between a lot owner and the body corporate committee, or between the body corporate and third parties such as contractors, managers, or the original developer. The most common categories relevant to sellers are:</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Noise and nuisance disputes</strong> between neighbouring lot owners are the most frequent but typically the least consequential for a sale. A dispute that has been through the BCCM conciliation process and resolved is generally not a material issue. An active, unresolved noise dispute involving your lot, particularly one that has generated formal complaints or adjudication proceedings, is more significant because it signals an ongoing problem that the buyer will inherit.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">By-law enforcement disputes</strong> arise when a lot owner is alleged to have breached the body corporate by-laws, for example through unapproved renovations, prohibited pets, or parking violations. If your lot is the subject of an active by-law enforcement proceeding, that is a material fact that must be disclosed. A buyer who takes title to a lot that is under a formal by-law enforcement order inherits that order.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Committee decision disputes</strong> occur when lot owners challenge a decision made by the body corporate committee, such as the approval of a major expenditure, the appointment or removal of a manager, or a change to the by-laws. These disputes can involve significant sums and can affect the financial position of the body corporate.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Building defect disputes</strong> are among the most serious and most consequential for sellers. When a body corporate has claims against the original builder or developer for defective construction, those proceedings can be lengthy, expensive, and uncertain in outcome. The financial exposure for individual lot owners can be material, and lenders may decline to fund purchases in buildings with active defect proceedings.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How disputes are resolved: the BCCM and QCAT process</h2>
      <p>The primary dispute resolution path for body corporate disputes in Queensland runs through the Commissioner for Body Corporate and Community Management (BCCM). The BCCM provides a conciliation service where a trained conciliator assists the parties to reach an agreed resolution. Conciliation is relatively quick, informal, and inexpensive, and many disputes are resolved at this stage without the need for formal adjudication.</p>

      <p>If conciliation fails or is not appropriate for the type of dispute, a party can apply to the BCCM for adjudication. An adjudicator is an independent decision-maker appointed by the Commissioner who reviews the evidence and issues a formal order. Adjudication orders are binding on the body corporate and all lot owners and can be enforced through the courts.</p>

      <p>For disputes that are not within the BCCM's jurisdiction, or where a party seeks to appeal an adjudicator's decision, the matter can proceed to QCAT, the Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal. QCAT proceedings are more formal, typically take longer, and involve greater legal costs than BCCM conciliation or adjudication. QCAT has broad jurisdiction over body corporate matters and its orders carry the force of a court judgment.</p>

      <p>Building defect disputes against builders and developers typically fall outside the BCCM regime and proceed through QCAT or the courts directly. These proceedings can span years and involve expert building reports, legal representation, and significant costs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a buyer's records search will find</h2>
      <p>When a buyer commissions a body corporate records search after going under contract, they receive access to the body corporate's records going back several years. This includes all committee and general meeting minutes, correspondence files, financial records, and any documents relating to disputes, BCCM applications, adjudication orders, and QCAT proceedings. A competent property solicitor reviewing those records will identify any active or recently resolved disputes and advise their client on the significance.</p>

      <p>There is no practical way for a seller to conceal dispute history that is documented in the body corporate records. BCCM applications are recorded, adjudication orders are filed, and committee minutes reference ongoing disputes. A seller who does not disclose an active dispute before contract, and whose buyer discovers it in the records search, has created a trust problem that is difficult to recover from. The buyer may seek a price reduction, impose additional conditions, or terminate the contract altogether.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The building defect scenario: what sellers in newer buildings need to know</h2>
      <p>Defective building work is a well-documented problem in Queensland's strata construction market, particularly in buildings completed between 2010 and 2020 when construction activity was very high. Common defects include water ingress through cladding or roof systems, fire safety non-compliance, structural cracks, and defective waterproofing. When the body corporate identifies significant defects and the builder has not remediated them, the body corporate typically pursues a claim through QCAT or the courts.</p>

      <p>For sellers in buildings with active defect proceedings, the implications are serious. Buyers cannot easily get finance for lots in buildings where there is unresolved structural or fire safety defect litigation. Buyers who do not need finance may still require a significant price discount to reflect the uncertainty of the outcome and the potential for a special levy if the proceedings are not fully successful. Sellers in this situation should obtain legal advice about their specific disclosure obligations before listing, and should discuss with their agent how the proceedings are likely to affect buyer interest and pricing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to check before your listing goes live</h2>
      <p>Before listing a unit or townhouse, request a body corporate records search or ask the body corporate manager directly about the following: Is there any active BCCM application involving your lot or the scheme? Has any adjudication order been made in the past two years? Is there any QCAT proceeding or court action involving the body corporate? Has any claim been made against the original builder or developer? Is there any dispute with the body corporate manager or management company?</p>

      <p>If the answer to any of these questions is yes, discuss the detail with your solicitor before signing the agency agreement. Understanding the nature and status of any dispute means you can disclose it accurately and price the property accordingly, rather than having it surface as an unwelcome surprise at the worst possible moment in your campaign.</p>

